        content:"How can we make evident the interconnectedness of landscapes not only locally but also at a distance? How can we make visible and narrate the diversity of relationships with communities that seem distant but are connected by shared histories, matter, atmosphere, people, non-human beings, and technologies?<br><br>At this symposium, we took a broader look through the lens of diverse presentations that navigate relational landscapes by satellite, data, foot and sailboat.<br><br>With Arturo Escobar, Andrés Burbano, Amy Franceschini, Myriel Milićević, Giacomo Nanni, Thiago da Costa Oliveira, Lynda C. Olman, Birgit Schneider, Fidel Thomet and Alexandra Toland. <br><br>Visit the <a href='https://thatbastart.github.io/symposium/'>Symposium Website</a> for more information:<br><br><a href='https://thatbastart.github.io/symposium/'><img src='rl/symposium.webp' style='width:100%;height:auto;'></a><br><br>A highlight of the symposium was the following interview with the anthropologist Arturo Escobar:<br><br><iframe title='vimeo-player' src='https://player.vimeo.com/video/650809025?h=78014f7118' width='100%' height='auto' style='aspect-ratio:16/9;' frameborder='0' allowfullscreen></iframe>"
