let sr_content=[
    {
        x:-25,
        y:15,
        z:20,
        title:"Colonial Period - The ecological Imperialism",
        content:"<img src='sr/sara_8.webp' style='width:100%;height:auto'><span class='italic'>The epidemics that reached America</span><br><br><br>When we talk about the movement of species, we must mention the Colombian exchange. This term was first used by Alfred W. Cosby in his book The Columbian Exchange: Biological and Cultural Consequences (1972). The Columbian Exchange is the process of biological unification between different continents that occurred since the first arrival of Columbus (1492). Then, humans started playing the role that geology and climate used to perform. We could say that, gradually, the biosphere started returning to the Pangea, reversing the separation caused by the continental drift. This exchange didn’t just occur in the trading context, but unintentionally, as in the case of several diseases (flu, measles...) that travelled unilaterally from Europe and Asia to the so called “New World”. Albert W. Cosby divided the procces of the Coumbian Exchange in three sections: plants, animals and diseases, but it wasn’t just about that. The different continents exchanged knowledge, culture and habits. Maybe it’s wrong to call it exchange, considering that the way it happened was deeply unequal, having disastrous consequences for the indigenous communities that still linger nowadays. That’s why it would be more accurate to talk about ecological imperialism.<br><br>"
    },
    {
        x:-23,
        y:10,
        z:35,
        title:"Plants",
        content:"<img src='sr/sara_10.webp' style='width:100%;height:auto'><span class='italic'>The first aclimatation garden in Paris, opened in 1860</span><br><br><br>From the beginning, plants were moved for food purposes, so most of them became domesticated species suitable for agriculture. However, some plants (e.g. tobacco) were moved with a different intention. After the XVIII. Century the use of plants for ornamental purposes became more common in the wealthier countries (the correlation between the wealth of a country and the arrival of exotic species is well known). Originally, this decorative use was concentrated in acclimatization gardens. Those institutions were intended to introduce “exotic” species from America in Europe for the pleasure of visitors. This historical episode of Europe is particularly cruel because the exhibition sometimes included people from the colonized communities. These people were forced to live in a reconstructed environment.<br><br>"
    },
    {
        x:-25,
        y:-14,
        z:35,
        title:"Potatoes",
        content:"<img src='sr/sara_9.webp' style='width:100%;height:auto'><br>The potato was first cultivated in Peru and Bolivia and came to Germany in 1647. However, due to its rapid growth and simple cultivation methods, it was considered a pagan food. For this reason, the potato was initially used only to decorate elegant gardens. But Friedrich II the Great had to introduce it to the regular diet to combat the famines raging in his empire, of which Potsdam was the capital. His marketing campaign was curious, but very effective. He began to include the potato in royal court dishes and issued the Potato Edicts, in which he urged high society to show that the potato was a pleasant food. If it was suitable for the upper class, it had to be the same for the rural population. It also had the support of religion, with priests called \"tuber preachers\" who were charged with spreading all knowledge about the cultivation and culinary use of the potato.<br><br>Finally, he decided to plant the potato in his own garden and guard it strictly. Nevertheless, he talked to the guards so that people could steal the potato without consequences. »If it's well protected, it must be worth it« is a logical argument, and people thought the same way. With this reverse psychology, he achieved that the potato became a staple food for the people's diet and that more land was available for its cultivation to effectively fight the famines. Nowadays, the potato is still very important as it is a part of the typical German dishes. This part of his reign earned him the nickname \"Potato King\" and his tomb always bears potatoes in his honor.<br><br><img src='sr/sara_2.webp' style='width:100%;height:auto'><span class='italic'>Solanum Tuberosum</span><br><br>"
    },
    {
        x:-15,
        y:4,
        z:42,
        title:"Tobacco",
        content:"<img src='sr/sara_3.webp' style='width:100%;height:auto'><span class='italic'>Moderate tobacco cultivation areas in Brandenburg nowadays</span><br><br><br>Tobacco originated in the Andes and came to Germany in 1565, where it was called \"Holy Herb\". Following the example of England, it was inhaled. It was first grown in Rhineland-Palatinate, where the tradition of tobacco cultivation continues to this day. During the Thirty Years' War, soldiers brought tobacco to the High Rin, and the first tobacco factories were established around Basel. In 1900, there were around 300 tobacco factories in the Hohen Rin. Other regions that also thrived on tobacco cultivation were Baden-Würtemberg, Bavaria and Brandenburg. Like other European countries, Germany grew tobacco because of import restrictions and rapidly increasing demand, along with the law that required a certain percentage of the national product (German tobacco was always intended for domestic consumption). Nevertheless, the proportion of tobacco grown in the country was still quite small, as the large factories mainly used tobacco from the United States, Cuba or Brazil.<br><br>Tobacco was introduced to the Uckermark region (Brandenburg) 400 years ago by the French Huguenots. There are still farms that grow it, but the industry is faced with becoming extinct.<br><br><img src='sr/sara_4.webp' style='width:100%;height:auto'><span class='italic'>Nicotiana Tabacum</span><br><br>"
    },
    {
        x:-5,
        y:-15,
        z:40,
        title:"Turkey",
        content:"<img src='sr/sara_5.webp' style='width:100%;height:auto'><br>The turkey was domesticated by the Aztecs in Mexico, where it had a close relationship with humans. In addition, the turkey had great importance in the symbolic and religious aspects of the Nahuas. In the cosmogonies of ancient Mexico, they are described as people transformed by a flood of fire. Perhaps the connection between fire and turkey is that, according to the Legend of the Five Suns*, the turkey was the only bird available in times of drought. But the turkey's cultural value was not only spiritual: it was also an important part of the diet of several indigenous communities.<br><br>The colonists referred to the turkey as the \"ground hen\" because of its similarity to Spanish chickens. Nevertheless, turkeys had great gastronomic success due to their delicious flavor and high fat content. It was one of the first species introduced by Columbus to the Catholic kings, and soon became a popular dish among the Spanish nobility. An example of this is the way it was served to Carlos I at the banquet celebrating his coronation in 1530. Thus, turkey gradually became a common dish for special occasions, not only in the United States but also in Germany, where Thanksgiving is celebrated as a religious and rural tradition.<br><br>As in the rest of Europe, there are no wild turkey populations in Germany. There are only domesticated animals for gastronomic purposes. Even domestic populations in Germany have not had much success in the past. For example, the populations in Austria collapsed when they were not maintained due to the Second World War. In the XX century there were eleven attempts to establish turkeys in Germany, all of which failed.<br><br>*The Aztec myth describes how the Earth and all living things were created and the role played by the gods. Each sun corresponds to a period in which a deity ruled.<br><br><img src='sr/sara_6.webp' style='width:100%;height:auto'><span class='italic'>Meleagris gallopavo</span><br><br>"
    },
    {
        x:-30,
        y:-12,
        z:55,
        title:"Since the XX Century - New determining Factors",
        content:"<img src='sr/sara_7.webp' style='width:100%;height:auto'><br><br>For obvious reasons, the farmable and rancher species were introduced in Europe since the second journey of Columbus (1493). Those species (rice went to America, or turkey to Europe) were exchanged in both directions for the benefit of the colonizers. However, most of American plants arrive as ornaments (even the edible ones), so, until the XVIII century, the cultivation of the American species doesn’t become widespread. In the same century, exploratory voyages increased, with the “climatization” of exotic species being the main direction of research. Exchanges between domesticated species took place in both directions, but not the transport of species kept for ornamental purposes. These profoundly unequal trade conditions persist to this day, as Amazon countries do not benefit from the illegal trade of their species (mainly birds) entering richer countries.<br><br>During the XX century, the mechanisms of introduction of \"exotic\" species have changed dramatically. On the one hand, the speed of transport technology and the ability to transport living organisms increased. Transport routes became shorter, allowing the transport of less resistant or long-lived species. Another crucial factor was the better lifestyle in wealthy countries. With this, long-distance tourism became more common, as did exotic pets and facilities such as zoos and aquariums.<br><br>"
    },
    {
        x:-10,
        y:-13,
        z:55,
        title:"Invasive Species",
        content:"<img src='sr/sara_12.webp' style='width:100%;height:auto'><span class='italic'>Nasua nasua</span><br><br><br>An invasive species is intentionally or unintentionally introduced into a new habitat, becomes established, and threatens native biodiversity and ecosystems. The spread of invasive species has worsened due to climate change. The economic impact of such species is enormous: in Europe, the cost of controlling and repairing the damage they cause is estimated at around $12 billion, and various primary sectors (such as fisheries) are also affected. The threat posed by these species is also genetic, as they sometimes interbreed with native species, creating new species that further alter the habitat. The effects of a biological invasion can even affect human health by causing new allergies or even being toxic (such as the giant parsley). The main reason for their arrival is the trade in \"exotic\" species, a crime that generates about $20 billion each year (and is even legal in some countries). Responsible are also, among others, the pet abandonment, tourism or the fur industry.<br><br>"
    },
    {
        x:0,
        y:-12,
        z:55,
        title:"Mink",
        content:"<img src='sr/sara_13.webp' style='width:100%;height:auto'><br>The American mink is a small predator that is classified as invasive in Europe. It is indeed a threat to biodiversity as it successfully hunts and thus exerts strong pressure on many species of fish, amphibians and small mammals. It has displaced the European mink to a large extent. The mink can spread very well, but the cause of its presence in Europe is the fur industry. Because of its shiny and beautiful fur, the mink is most often used for the production of clothing (such as coats). They spread in the 20th century, when the first fur companies were established and many mink disappeared from farms for lack of safety precautions.<br><br>People usually talk about how harmful these animals are to the environment and biodiversity, but not about the industry that brought them to Europe in the first place, which is particularly cruel. To make their hair more striking, the species has even been genetically modified to create blue or silver specimens. Fortunately, mink farms in Germany are disappearing (many were closed between 2017 and 2018), bringing the country closer to the government's goal of animal welfare.<br><br><img src='sr/sara_14.webp' style='width:100%;height:auto'><span class='italic'>Neovison vison</span><br><br>"
    },
    {
        x:5,
        y:-12,
        z:48,
        title:"American Red Crab",
        content:"<img src='sr/sara_15.webp' style='width:100%;height:auto'><br>The American red crab originates from northern Mexico. These crustaceans are not demanding: like other invasive species, they eat almost anything they can find. Worms, fish, snails or non-adult amphibians, the most endangered family of species. The red crab has a high and rapid reproduction rate and is also a carrier of a fungal disease (Aphanomyces astaci) that does not affect it but causes great harm to native crabs. In this way, in the waters where this crab has been introduced, the native species will inevitably become extinct. The red crab also damages the soil and plants (especially rice), as it is a great digger.<br><br>This crustacean is important in gastronomy, so it is bred in different parts of the world and escapes from aquariums. Because of its shiny color, it is also popular as a pet, and probably some specimens were abandoned by their owners when they got tired of them. In Europe it was first sighted in the south of the Iberian Peninsula, but now it is quite common in Germany, and it also reaches the north of Europe. The summer of 2017 was quite wet in Berlin, so some parts were flooded, which led to several unexpected effects. One of them was that numerous red crayfish wandered in the streets in the Tiergarten area: they were looking for a new habitat. Although the Berlin authorities successfully pushed them back, unfortunately there are already specimens in the Havel River (Brandenburg).<br><br><img src='sr/sara_16.webp' style='width:100%;height:auto'><span class='italic'>Procambarus clarkii</span><br><br>"
    }
];

